<subSubSection id="FDC3B51027E8CDB4220072DB9B61C8A4" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="D94AC072E4F3DDE67705AA7503C2C303" pageNumber="66">Discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1DCA06B87AA86E0233B45D4792361E02" pageNumber="66">
The traditional “working diagnosis” of 
<taxonomicName id="6EBF5B863C3AB43186E95D4479278CA0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
was based strongly on meristics, especially on the high number of dorsal and anal fin elements, with formulae D. XVII-XX,8-11 and A. VII-XII,6-9. There have been also morphometric attributes, albeit rather general: the pectoral fin reaching or exceeding the anal fin origin; body somewhat deep; snout short, mouth rather small, maxilla not reaching the orbital rim, neither vertically nor horizontally; teeth in the outer row subequal in size anteriorly in both jaws (Regan 1905; Kullander 1996; Greenfield &amp; Thomerson 1997; Miller et al. 2005). No synapomorphies were known for 
<taxonomicName id="CB3578DB031FBBAAADCF44B80D72B1E1" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DAD83DE21AD1CDC794B05062478B4FC6" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:273F29E5-91F4-45BE-8447-659BDE8939E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Cryptoheros Allgayer 2001" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Cryptoheros</taxonomicName>
, or 
<taxonomicName id="DFBA8397E88E7A217EEF35E50B0E63DB" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7A9BA3FB-1462-4C73-A40A-F9A660B3AA90" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypsophrys Agassiz 1859:408" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hypsophrys</taxonomicName>
, but some of these traditionally diagnostic characters have turned out to be synapomorphic, e.g. the number of anal-fin spines for 
<taxonomicName id="E1C7A44133FE2ACAEB3BB38BB9C4BE55" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
; others, as expected, were convergent, e.g. the length of the maxilla (Schmitter-Soto, in press). Still others, such as body depth, are useful for alpha-level taxonomy, but not for phylogeny reconstruction (Zelditch et al. 2005).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E8F712BC35D7719428F7D657D724E0C8" lastPageNumber="67" pageNumber="66">
Allgayer (2001) had already expressed the view that 
<taxonomicName id="5B2A9E9DD1767B7053D33378C13C316B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
should be restricted to 
<taxonomicName id="D2C042259E6256E1AA9A9200C419CFF7" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="centrarchus">Ar. centrarchus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="02DC970AA6CDFA7E7636C1FC0C9C9917" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="spinosissimus">Ar. spinosissimus</taxonomicName>
. Burgess (2000) judged that 
<taxonomicName id="7E674F1300073891F5E39DD73FC62569" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="multispinosus">Ar. multispinosus</taxonomicName>
should be added too, and Allgayer (2001) 
<pageStartToken id="76BA4D8BA1DF0CBF059E7317BB77D119" pageNumber="67">himself</pageStartToken>
included 
<taxonomicName id="C7063E8521FDF0D073BF4F6EC5A11909" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4B9BCDD6-7318-4D82-B13F-E89502F50F24" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Herotilapia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Herotilapia Pellegrin 1904:(165) 247" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Herotilapia</taxonomicName>
in his subtribe Archocentrina (= 
<taxonomicName id="E16DC8F3383525803ACFEF172EF2DA96" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="72CBB89630BF1C6B148B49932DEA42E8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Amatitlania" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Amatitlania</taxonomicName>
+ [
<taxonomicName id="D238BCBBB175700A1B1FF9AF77707AD9" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:273F29E5-91F4-45BE-8447-659BDE8939E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Cryptoheros Allgayer 2001" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Cryptoheros</taxonomicName>
without 
<taxonomicName id="913E98D376F816C76D97FDE4D9D25C75" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="panamensis">Cr. panamensis</taxonomicName>
], a group for which Schmitter-Soto [in press], found no support). This opinion, although only recently published explicitly, is a venerable one: Regan (1908) called 
<taxonomicName id="C1BEE3DBEECBBE1D0C7E8E0EDF3CBF07" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4B9BCDD6-7318-4D82-B13F-E89502F50F24" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Herotilapia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Herotilapia Pellegrin 1904:(165) 247" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Herotilapia</taxonomicName>
“evidently closely allied” to 
<taxonomicName id="C690B398D36B7ADB63B7036C3CA626BC" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
. Other authors, e.g. Bussing (1976), have considered 
<taxonomicName id="C3CED0A82F4F3B68368510001231E4DC" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4B9BCDD6-7318-4D82-B13F-E89502F50F24" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Herotilapia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Herotilapia Pellegrin 1904:(165) 247" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Herotilapia</taxonomicName>
“derived” from 
<taxonomicName id="03E050676BE2A92DE2C9C23B41FBF598" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E62CB1A8517266043079120262662865" pageNumber="67">
However, most molecular phylogenetic hypotheses (Martin &amp; Bermingham 1998; Farias et al. 2004; Hulsey et al. 2004; Concheiro 
<normalizedToken id="2C89D9431D12D2C8223FF40210D45FF4" originalValue="Pérez">Perez</normalizedToken>
et al. 2007 -all based on the cytochrome b gene) have found 
<taxonomicName id="BC5C8B74116ACBED7C5C305EA9D6F6B8" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4B9BCDD6-7318-4D82-B13F-E89502F50F24" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Herotilapia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Herotilapia Pellegrin 1904:(165) 247" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Herotilapia</taxonomicName>
quite unrelated from 
<taxonomicName id="286B3F0E27890937F6AC79ACABCF9502" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
and allies. A possible explanation for this pattern may lie on the intrinsic limitations of cytochrome b. As stated by Martin &amp; Bermingham (1998), “ heroine cichlids… are unfortunately refractory to phylogenetic inference using cytochrome b sequences.” Long branches are common in “dwarf” Neotropical cichlids, such as species of 
<taxonomicName id="986A6789C4980D7D4EF38146490C05B0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
and allies, and the cytochrome b gene presents saturation at third-codon position (Farias et al. 2004). Other genes should provide interesting independent evidence to settle the issue.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E33392DC9996D383B04A05F6EE4FD674" pageNumber="67">
My understanding of 
<taxonomicName id="F0B7F82B11F4A4E824D119EDC2CDD0A7" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:273F29E5-91F4-45BE-8447-659BDE8939E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Cryptoheros Allgayer 2001" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Cryptoheros</taxonomicName>
diverges from Allgayer’s (2001), who included also what is here called 
<taxonomicName id="B8A65452F634C82706871D1066A497B8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Amatitlania" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Amatitlania</taxonomicName>
, and excluded 
<taxonomicName id="72C231382775F2B0A461289F74BFFA2D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="panamensis">Cr. panamensis</taxonomicName>
. On the other hand, Kullander (2003), who did not recognize 
<taxonomicName id="CDEEF4FF98F4AC0E908EE92C8D36C233" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:273F29E5-91F4-45BE-8447-659BDE8939E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Cryptoheros Allgayer 2001" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Cryptoheros</taxonomicName>
, decided to call this species 
<taxonomicName id="42F05604EC810F274CF023E1ED1812C8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="panamensis">Archocentrus panamensis</taxonomicName>
, recognizing that its affinities do not lie with 
<taxonomicName id="D7E010B456E7968C4ACF6423D8B29E77" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E80528E6-4EC5-48D2-9B49-38E85C7886AF" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus Günther 1867:603" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Neetroplus</taxonomicName>
(nor with 
<taxonomicName id="E957FC35B14EE0E272B78E835D4444A7" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7A9BA3FB-1462-4C73-A40A-F9A660B3AA90" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypsophrys Agassiz 1859:408" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hypsophrys</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName id="CE47DAE2DC879A57A98F56072F2EE27F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Amatitlania" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigrofasciata">Am. nigrofasciata</taxonomicName>
had been considered a 
<taxonomicName id="6B8A839CDB54F83507E4D0C1A98E6461" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:273F29E5-91F4-45BE-8447-659BDE8939E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Cryptoheros Allgayer 2001" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Cryptoheros</taxonomicName>
by Allgayer (2001) and an 
<taxonomicName id="0C2E40F048A17382B869A8C1345764ED" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
by Kullander (2003).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1362830E0EB1AFB2B2A7A65895D1E6AC" pageNumber="67">
<taxonomicName id="5D2C41968441BA77C6E290ACF49BF53D" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E80528E6-4EC5-48D2-9B49-38E85C7886AF" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus Günther 1867:603" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Neetroplus</taxonomicName>
has had a rather unfortunate usage history. Based on a very distinctive but overrated dental character (like the tricuspid teeth of 
<taxonomicName id="62C4AA3C5499119BB037A1A48F183B1C" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4B9BCDD6-7318-4D82-B13F-E89502F50F24" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Herotilapia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Herotilapia Pellegrin 1904:(165) 247" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Herotilapia</taxonomicName>
), monotypic at first, it became an artificial group with the inclusion of several incisor-toothed cichlids, such as 
<taxonomicName id="77ACF939D79A1BF221E90A2A6D51D902" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A6E61CB3-96A1-496F-BF62-312ED4C6D0C2" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus carpintis Jordan &amp; Snyder 1899:146" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carpintis">N. carpintis Jordan &amp; Snyder, 1899</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName id="B4739895BEBA026104E243B792500BD3" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Herichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carpintis">Herichthys carpintis</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName id="6437E3433BF215F85A6A2C4271E76E23" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:18131267-24B7-479F-824F-C80F8D0703F0" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus bocourti Vaillant &amp; Pellegrin 1902:85 [1]" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bocourti">N. bocourti Vaillant &amp; Pellegrin, 1902</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName id="09D2291507A9301D79132974AFF0E248" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cichlasoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bocourti">‘Cichlasoma’ bocourti</taxonomicName>
), and 
<taxonomicName id="51BED07EEA89B9D398D3D03B6E05720F" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:2411EEF8-6445-445C-AFA1-B6C5A08A5161" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus panamensis Meek &amp; Hildebrand 1913:90" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="panamensis">N. panamensis</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName id="85B2B329B04E470BE35BCDAAACA0B0F6" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="panamensis">Cr. panamensis</taxonomicName>
). Among this assemblage, 
<taxonomicName id="56E7126CA885F30E7D9C0E3184BE6DFF" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nematopus">H. nematopus</taxonomicName>
is the only species to have incisor teeth as juvenile (Rogers 1981).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="141DC0821A48EAFF3F80602B3EE7C21B" pageNumber="67">
The synonymization of 
<taxonomicName id="A0505BA44FDDD36A0ED80EB58CB7C826" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E80528E6-4EC5-48D2-9B49-38E85C7886AF" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus Günther 1867:603" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Neetroplus</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName id="BF1EB7F21F5DF5E8128131EA69D28B73" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7A9BA3FB-1462-4C73-A40A-F9A660B3AA90" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypsophrys Agassiz 1859:408" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hypsophrys</taxonomicName>
has the disadvantage of obliterating a widely used name (
<taxonomicName id="8BE2D52B154063DC32B8B1636950F9F4" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:6D4EDCB3-9A89-4702-A37B-4B203C5A2EE2" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus nematopus Günther 1867:603" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nematopus">Neetroplus nematopus</taxonomicName>
). However, a classification should also convey information about phylogeny, and this purpose is not served well by recognizing two monotypic sister genera instead of calling their clade by just one generic name. An example of this stance is the synonymization of 
<taxonomicName id="308AFD45A5E37B409BA63613749FE6EF" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C2F2D5C0-62DA-4FC4-85BE-C3214B17F216" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinodontidae" genus="Garmanella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Garmanella Hubbs 1936:218" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Garmanella</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName id="3114E8CD0B027A87371B887B40D16B4B" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:CC1B2940-9BCF-4EFE-9D61-98754E8B6AEC" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinodontidae" genus="Jordanella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Jordanella Goode &amp; Bean 1879:117" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Jordanella</taxonomicName>
(Cyprinodontidae), in “…the interest of having generic categories define derived groups, rather than recognize individual differences…” (Parenti 1981). Moreover, the sister-group relationship of 
<taxonomicName id="E0CD061FB225108F52841825FF693070" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nicaraguensis">H. nicaraguensis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D6384076610315B2E611A9800F9172BA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nematopus">H. nematopus</taxonomicName>
is supported by most proposed phylogenies (e.g. Martin &amp; Bermingham 1998; Hulsey et al. 2004; Concheiro 
<normalizedToken id="72B2E3CD74D5DADE320C670AB4CEC882" originalValue="Pérez">Perez</normalizedToken>
et al. 2007).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D2C47A91E19EBBC8A76CD2CE1821FAB9" pageNumber="67">
It should be acknowledged that a classification alternative to the one here proposed, and equally congruent with the phylogeny presented by Schmitter-Soto (in press), might include all species dealt with in this work in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="BC2DC22AD66DE13550935537189D7C16" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7A9BA3FB-1462-4C73-A40A-F9A660B3AA90" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypsophrys Agassiz 1859:408" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hypsophrys</taxonomicName>
(or 
<taxonomicName id="5E9D135B2B8C604D2F476635B0764BDF" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:60986D0C-086A-4E68-8914-90992063465B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Amphilophus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Amphilophus Agassiz 1859:408" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Amphilophus</taxonomicName>
, or 
<taxonomicName id="FC26DB6FFFA2241244DA8DBEF37D513A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Parachromis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Parachromis</taxonomicName>
, all three names having been proposed in the same work, on the same page -Kullander &amp; Hartel 1997). It is my opinion, notwithstanding, that the classification proposed here is more informative, and also less disruptive with recent usage. On the other hand, since the aim of this work is to review the species formerly assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="CE60034228D34DDB398DB894EC157C20" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
, the choice of taxa was not ideal for such higher level decisions.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BD4261165EC8F9E9D81C9E6EDB9938D5" lastPageNumber="68" pageNumber="67">
I follow the Evolutionary Species Concept (ESC). However, the ESC is not an operational concept; to be able to recognize species under the ESC (i.e., every lineage that “maintains its identity from other such lineages and which has its own evolutionary tendencies and historical fate”: Wiley 1978), I applied here both the “autapomorphic” and the “diagnosable” versions of the Phylogenetic Species Concept (PSC) (Mayden 1997): every species should display at least one derived character of its own (Rosen 1979), but, if a non-homoplastic (unique) autapomorphy is not found, then “the smallest diagnosable cluster of individual organisms within which there is a [presumed] parental pattern of ancestry and descent” (Cracraft 1983) is to be recognized as a species. Thus, I agree with Lucena et al. (1992), who point out that “to consider two distinguishable populations 
<pageStartToken id="BCAD923F42B19518D289366FA3390304" pageNumber="68">as</pageStartToken>
a single species [implies] loss of information about phylogeny and biogeography.”
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E5AED9ABAA3C3095851576ED5A482561" pageNumber="68">
The phylogeny and biogeography of the species formerly assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="A071E02DD27F80B6AC6CDD915701F2E5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="68" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
are discussed by Schmitter-Soto (in press).
</paragraph>
